    <segment id="1" parent="12" relname="background">To reinforce this concept as well as some we have already discussed, we could also 
connect flexibility, learnability and efficiency.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="6" relname="nonvolitional-cause"> It could very well be that a system is 
flexible (provides different ways to perform the same function),</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="9" relname="span"> but that MIGHT effect 
learnability.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="11" relname="span"> With more than one way to perform a function, one has to learn and retain in 
memory how to do the same thing in different ways.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="10" relname="span">  There is where the efficiency 
aspect comes through.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="7" relname="condition">  When the process is logical and intuitive, and learned once,</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="8" relname="span"> then 
there is a good chance that flexibility will be a positive thing.</segment>
